# Building an NPM Package for Your Icons

Here's a step-by-step guide to create an NPM package for your icon collection:

## 1. Set Up Your Project Structure

```
my-icons/
├── icons/              # Your icon files (SVG, PNG, etc.)
├── src/                # Source code
│   ├── index.js        # Main entry point
│   └── components/     # React components (if applicable)
├── package.json
├── README.md
├── .gitignore
└── .npmignore
```

## 2. Initialize Your Package

```bash
mkdir my-icons
cd my-icons
npm init
```

Answer the prompts to create your `package.json` file.

## 3. Configure Your Package.json

```json
{
  "name": "my-icons",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "description": "My custom icon library",
  "main": "dist/index.js",
  "files": [
    "dist",
    "icons"
  ],
  "scripts": {
    "build": "your-build-command-here",
    "prepublishOnly": "npm run build"
  },
  "keywords": ["icons", "ui"],
  "author": "Your Name",
  "license": "MIT"
}
```

## 4. Create Your Index File

Depending on how you want to expose your icons, create an appropriate entry point:

### For React Components

```javascript
// src/index.js
import React from 'react';

// Import all your SVG icons
const iconContext = require.context('../icons', false, /\.svg$/);
const iconNames = iconContext.keys();

// Create an object with all icons
const icons = {};
iconNames.forEach(path => {
  const iconName = path.replace(/\.\/(.*)\.svg$/, '$1');
  icons[iconName] = props => (
    <img 
      src={require(`../icons/${iconName}.svg`).default} 
      alt={iconName} 
      {...props} 
    />
  );
});

export default icons;
```

### For Direct Access to Icon Files

```javascript
// src/index.js
// This approach lets users directly import icon files
const iconContext = require.context('../icons', false, /\.(svg|png)$/);
const icons = {};

iconContext.keys().forEach(path => {
  const iconName = path.replace(/\.\/(.*)\.svg$/, '$1');
  icons[iconName] = iconContext(path).default;
});

export default icons;
```

## 5. Build Setup

Choose a build tool (Webpack, Rollup, etc.) to bundle your code. For a simple setup with Webpack:

```bash
npm install --save-dev webpack webpack-cli babel-loader @babel/core @babel/preset-env @babel/preset-react
```

Create a `webpack.config.js`:

```javascript
const path = require('path');

module.exports = {
  entry: './src/index.js',
  output: {
    path: path.resolve(__dirname, 'dist'),
    filename: 'index.js',
    libraryTarget: 'umd',
    library: 'MyIcons',
    umdNamedDefine: true,
    globalObject: 'this'
  },
  module: {
    rules: [
      {
        test: /\.jsx?$/,
        exclude: /node_modules/,
        use: {
          loader: 'babel-loader',
          options: {
            presets: ['@babel/preset-env', '@babel/preset-react']
          }
        }
      },
      {
        test: /\.(svg|png)$/,
        use: ['file-loader']
      }
    ]
  },
  externals: {
    react: 'react',
    'react-dom': 'react-dom'
  }
};
```

Update your build script in package.json:

```json
"scripts": {
  "build": "webpack --mode production"
}
```

## 6. Create .npmignore File

```
node_modules
src
.babelrc
webpack.config.js
.gitignore
```

## 7. Build and Publish

```bash
npm run build
npm publish
```

## Using Your Package

Once published, users can install and use your icon package:

```bash
npm install my-icons
```

```javascript
// Using the icons in another project
import icons from 'my-icons';

// If you exported React components
function App() {
  return <div>{icons.myIconName({ className: 'icon' })}</div>;
}

// If you exported file paths
function App() {
  return <img src={icons.myIconName} alt="Icon" />;
}
```

## Alternative Approach: Individual Imports

For better tree-shaking, you might want to support individual imports:

```javascript
// src/index.js
export { default as Icon1 } from './components/Icon1';
export { default as Icon2 } from './components/Icon2';
// etc.
```

Then users can:

```javascript
import { Icon1, Icon2 } from 'my-icons';
```

This setup gives you a flexible way to share and use your icon collection across projects!
